/> ATTACK IN ITS TRACKS.</p><p>From an anonymous doctor:</p><p>Summary:&#8221;The very first symptoms of ebola are exactly the<br
/> same as scurvy, which is caused by inadequate vitamin C.  Though scurvy<br
/> is seldom fatal as a primary condition, scurvy also represents only a<br
/> partial deficiency of vitamin C, the body still has a LOT of vitamin C<br
/> compared to zero, which ebola causes.  Absent ANY vitamin C, blood<br
/> vessels become very weak and start to lose blood, and platelets become<br
/> ineffective and unable to trigger clots.  So death by ebola is caused by<br
/> massive internal bleeding and loss of blood, which can be stopped<br
/> simply by taking enormous doses of vitamin C until the immune system<br
/> succeeds in killing off the virus.&#8221;</p><p>Begin text:<br
/> Ebola is probably the best known of a class of viruses known as<br
/> hemorrhagic fever viruses. In fact, Ebola virus was initially recognized<br
/> in 1976. Other less known but related viral syndromes include yellow<br
/> fever, dengue hemorrhagic fever, Rift Valley fever, Crimean-Congo<br
/> hemorrhagic fever, Kyasanur Forest disease, Omsk hemorrhagic fever,<br
/> hemorrhagic fever with renal syndrome, Hantavirus pulmonary syndrome,<br
/> Venezuelan hemorrhagic fever, Brazilian hemorrhagic fever, Argentine<br
/> hemorrhagic fever, Bolivian hemorrhagic fever, and Lassa fever. The<br
/> Ebola virus infection, also known as African hemorrhagic fever, has the<br
/> distinction of having the highest case-fatality rate of the viral<br
/> infections noted above, ranging from 53% to 88%.</p><p>These viral hemorrhagic fever syndromes share certain clinical features.<br
/> The Cecil Textbook of Medicine notes that these diseases are<br
/> characterized by capillary fragility, which translates to easy bleeding,<br
/> that can frequently lead to severe shock and death. These diseases also<br
/> tend to consume and/or destroy the platelets, which play an integral<br
/> role in blood clotting. The clinical presentation of these viral<br
/> diseases is similar to scurvy, which is also characterized by capillary<br
/> fragility and a tendency to bleed easily. Characteristic skin lesions<br
/> develop, which are actually multiple tiny areas of bleeding into the<br
/> skin that surround the hair follicles. some cases even include bleeding<br
/> into already healed scars.</p><p>In the classic form of scurvy that evolves very slowly from the gradual<br
/> depletion of vitamin C body stores, the immune system will be<br
/> sufficiently compromised for infection to claim the patient’s life<br
/> before the extensive hemorrhage that occurs after all vitamin C stores<br
/> have been completely exhausted.  Ebola virus and the other viral<br
/> hemorrhagic fevers are much more likely to cause hemorrhaging before<br
/> any other fatal infection has a chance to become established. This is<br
/> because the virus so rapidly and totally metabolizes and consumes all<br
/> available vitamin C in the bodies of the victims that an advanced stage<br
/> of scurvy is literally produced after only a few days of the disease.</p><p>The scurvy is so complete that the blood vessels generally cannot keep<br
/> from hemorrhaging long enough to allow an infective complication to<br
/> develop. Also, the viral hemorrhagic fevers typically only take<br
/> hold and reach epidemic proportions in those populations that would<br
/> already be expected to have low body stores of vitamin C, such as is<br
/> found in many of the severely malnourished Africans. In such<br
/> individuals, an infecting hemorrhagic virus will often wipe out any<br
/> remaining vitamin C stores before the immune systems can get the upper<br
/> hand and initiate recovery. When the vitamin C stores are<br
/> rapidly depleted by large infecting doses of an aggressive virus, the<br
/> immune system gets similarly depleted and compromised. However, this<br
/> point is largely academic after hemorrhaging throughout the body has<br
/> begun.</p><p>To date, no viral infection has been demonstrated to be resistant to the<br
/> proper dosing of vitamin C as classically demonstrated by Klenner.<br
/> However, not all viruses have been treated with Klenner-sized vitamin C<br
/> doses, or at least the results have not been published. Ebola viral<br
/> infection and the other acute viral hemorrhagic fevers appear to be<br
/> diseases that fall into this category. Because of the seemingly<br
/> exceptional ability of these viruses to rapidly deplete vitamin C<br
/> stores, even larger doses of vitamin C would likely be required in order<br
/> to effectively reverse and eventually cure infections caused by these<br
/> viruses.</p><p>Cathcart (1981), who introduced the concept of bowel tolerance to<br
/> vitamin C discussed earlier, hypothesized that Ebola and the other acute<br
/> viral hemorrhagic fevers may well require 500,000 mg of vitamin C daily<br
/> to reach bowel tolerance! Whether this estimate is accurate, it seems<br
/> clear as evidenced by the scurvy-like clinical manifestations of these<br
/> infections that vitamin C dosing must be vigorous and given in extremely<br
/> high doses. If the disease seems to be winning, then even more vitamin C<br
/> should be given until symptoms begin to lessen. Obviously, these are<br
/> viral diseases that would absolutely require high doses of vitamin C<br
/> intravenously as the initial therapy. The oral administration should<br
/> begin simultaneously, but the intravenous route should not be abandoned<br
/> until the clinical response is complete. Death occurs too quickly with<br
/> the hemorrhagic fevers to be conservative when dosing the vitamin C.<br
/> (from Vitamin C, Infectious Diseases, and Toxins:Curing the Incurable<br
/> by Thomas E. Levy MD JD)</p><p>MY COMMENT: I may not be a doctor, but I am awful good with<br
